                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="62522" author="linda" created="Thu, 18 Jul 2013 01:50:14 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Change merged 7/16&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="62133" author="linda" created="Thu, 11 Jul 2013 17:42:09 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Changes are ready for review at &lt;a href=&quot;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/6941/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/6941/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="56733" author="brett" created="Mon, 22 Apr 2013 20:16:56 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;1.  brw_stats - &quot;discontiguous pages&quot; refers to data from a client in an RPC that is not in contiguous pages, indicating small or random IO.&lt;br/&gt;
2.  brw_stats - &quot;discontiguous blocks&quot; refers to an IO operation that did not write sequential blocks of data, such as would be seen with small or random IO.&lt;br/&gt;
3.  brw_stats - &quot;disk fragmented I/Os&quot; refers to writing to fragmented files, indicating there are not sufficient sequential blocks available on target.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="56718" author="brett" created="Mon, 22 Apr 2013 18:41:35 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Clarification from Andreas on the meaning of discontiguous pages and blocks:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The distinction is that in brw_stats &quot;pages&quot; refer to what the client submitted in the RPC, while &quot;blocks&quot; refer to what the OST submitted to disk.  If there are discontiguous pages it means random or small IO submitted by the client.  Discontiguous blocks relate to on-disk fragmentation.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
